		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Tikkun olam</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<div class="dablink">For other related concepts, see <a href="/wiki/Tikkun" title="Tikkun">Tikkun</a>.</div>
<p><i><b>Tikkun olam</b></i> (<a href="/wiki/Hebrew_language" title="Hebrew language">Hebrew</a>: <span lang="he" dir="rtl" xml:lang="he"><b>תיקון עולם</b></span>‎) is a <a href="/wiki/Hebrew_language" title="Hebrew language">Hebrew</a> phrase that means, "repairing the world" or "perfecting the world." In <a href="/wiki/Judaism" title="Judaism">Judaism</a>, the concept of <i>tikkun olam</i> originated in the early rabbinic period. The concept was given new meanings in the <a href="/wiki/Kabbalah" title="Kabbalah">kabbalah</a> of the medieval period and further connotations in modern Judaism.</p>
